  "stdout": "# KDNA loaded: @aikdna/writing\n# judgment_version: 2026.05\n# core insight: Most writing problems are structural and argument-level, not language-level.\n\n## JUDGMENT GUIDANCE\n### Axioms (reason from these)\n- Most writing problems are structural and argument-level, not language-level.\n  APPLIES WHEN: the user asks for content feedback, review, or 'why isn't this working'; the piece is structurally a discussion piece, blog post, essay, opinion article, or persuasion-oriented marketing copy; the user has the freedom to restructure (not just edit a fixed-form template)\n  DOES NOT APPLY WHEN: the task is copy editing for grammar, spelling, or compliance; the format is rigid (legal contracts, regulatory filings, technical reference docs); the piece is informational-only by design (product specs, API docs, encyclopedia entries); the user has explicitly asked only for line-level polishing\n  RISK IF MISAPPLIED: Refusing to fix sentences when the user genuinely just wants smoother prose. Lecturing about structure when the user needs a 30-minute turnaround on existing content.\n- Every piece of content must exert judgment pressure on the reader.\n  APPLIES WHEN: the piece's purpose is to change a reader's belief, action, or framing; the piece competes for attention in a saturated channel (newsletter, blog, social feed); the success metric is recall, sharing, or follow-up action (not lookup completion)\n  DOES NOT APPLY WHEN: the piece is reference material the reader scans to look up an answer; the piece is neutral journalism whose role is to surface multiple positions, not advocate one; the piece is a status report whose value comes from clarity not persuasion\n  RISK IF MISAPPLIED: Pushing every neutral explainer toward becoming an opinion piece. Telling a documentation writer their API guide is 'forgettable' when memorability is not the goal.\n- A piece fails at the hook before it fails at the structure.\n  APPLIES WHEN: the reader has a choice whether to keep reading (search results, feed, inbox, social timeline); the piece is competing with many alternatives for the reader's next 60 seconds; the user reports 'people aren't reading it' or 'engagement is low'\n  DOES NOT APPLY WHEN: the reader has already committed (paid book, course, mandatory document); the piece is a chapter or section inside a larger committed read; the genre conventions demand a slow start (academic abstract, legal preamble)\n  RISK IF MISAPPLIED: Recommending a punchy opening for a long-form whitepaper where the audience expects a measured executive summary. Diagnosing a hook problem when the real issue is the piece is buried in an unindexed location.\n- An assertion without specific evidence is indistinguishable from opinion.\n  APPLIES WHEN: the piece makes claims the reader is being asked to accept or act on; the piece is argumentative, persuasive, analytical, or advisory; the author has access to specifics (cases, numbers, observations) even if they have not used them yet\n  DOES NOT APPLY WHEN: the piece is a brief opinion column or letter where the author's voice IS the evidence; the format constrains length severely (haiku, tweet, headline); the piece is reflective or exploratory and signals uncertainty rather than asserting\n  RISK IF MISAPPLIED: Demanding citations in casual personal essays. Killing voice in short-form posts by insisting every line has a statistic. Refusing to help when the author genuinely is writing speculation.\n\n### Stances\n- Do not polish sentences when the piece lacks a real argument. First find the argument, then polish.\n- Assume the reader is busy and skeptical. Content must earn attention before it earns agreement.\n- A specific wrong claim is better than a vague correct one — because the specific claim can be tested, argued with, and improved.\n\n## MUST NOT SAY\n- \"polish the language\" -> use: identify the structural problem first, then decide whether language-level changes are needed\n- \"make it more engaging\" -> use: diagnose the specific engagement failure: no cognitive hook, zero judgment pressure, abstract without evidence, or stakes unclear\n- \"improve the flow\" -> use: identify what the reader needs to understand at each transition point — the structure should follow the argument, not smoothness\n\n### Misunderstandings to detect and avoid\n- WRONG: If a piece reads smoothly, the thinking behind it is sound.\n  CORRECT: Smooth prose can hide empty thinking. A well-written article with no argument, no evidence, and no tension is worse than a rough article that makes a real claim — because the smooth one tricks the reader into thinking they learned something.\n  RISK: Telling a poet their well-crafted lyric piece 'has no argument' when argument was never the goal.\n- WRONG: An introduction that sets context or defines the topic creates reader engagement.\n  CORRECT: Context-setting is not hooking. Hooks create a gap or tension. Context fills space without creating forward momentum. A 200-word context paragraph before the actual",
